processLine = function(x){
  
  line = strsplit(x, split=";") 
  N = length(line[[1]]) 
  
  t = gsub("^t=","",line[[1]][1])
  time = vector(mode ="character", length = (N-4))
  time[] = t
  
  scan = gsub ("^id=","",line[[1]][2])
  scanMAC = vector(mode ="character", length = (N-4))
  scanMAC[] = scan
  
  Degree = gsub("^degree=","",line[[1]][4])
  orientation = vector(mode ="character", length = (N-4))
  orientation[] = Degree
  
  X = strsplit(gsub("^pos=","",line[[1]][3]), split=",")[[1]][1]
  posX = vector(mode ="character", length = (N-4))
  posX[] = X
  
  Y = strsplit(gsub("^pos=","",line[[1]][3]), split=",")[[1]][2]
  posY = vector(mode ="character", length = (N-4))
  posY[] = Y
  
  Z = strsplit(gsub("^pos=","",line[[1]][3]), split=",")[[1]][3]
  posZ = vector(mode ="character", length = (N-4))
  posZ[] = Z
  
  signal = sapply(line[[1]][5:N], FUN = function(x) 
    signal = strsplit(x, split="[=,]"))
  Signal = do.call(rbind, signal)
  
  m = cbind( time, scanMAC, orientation, posX, posY, posZ, Signal)
  matriX = matrix(m, nrow = N-4, ncol =10)
  
  return(matriX)                  
}

txt = readLines ("/Users/MAC/Desktop/Berkeley/2015Spring/Stat 133/hw/offline.final.trace.txt")
txt1 = grep( "^*t=", txt, value = TRUE)
tmp = lapply (txt1, processLine)

cleanData = function(data, keepMacs = c("00:14:bf:3b:c7:c6","00:14:bf:b1:97:81","00:14:bf:b1:97:8a","00:14:bf:b1:97:8d","00:14:bf:b1:97:90","00:0f:a3:39:e1:c0")){
  
  # Turn to numeric
  offline1 = data.frame(
    offline$time, offline$scanMac, 
    as.numeric( as.character(offline$posX) ), 
    as.numeric( as.character(offline$posY) ), 
    as.numeric( as.character(offline$posZ) ), 
    as.numeric( as.character(offline$orientation) ), 
    offline$mac,as.numeric( as.character(offline$signal) ), 
    offline$channel, offline$type)
  colnames(offline1) = c("time" , "scanMac", "posX", "posY", "posZ","orientation", "mac","signal", "channel", "type")
  
  # Rround orientation
  
  orienRound = round((offline1$orientation) / 45) * 45
  offline2 = cbind(orienRound, offline1)
  
  # Remove duplicated rows
  offline2 = offline2[-which(duplicated(offline2)),]
  
  # Remove adhoc devices
  dataframe0 = offline2[ -which(offline2$type == "1"),]
  
  test1 = dataframe0[which(dataframe0$mac == keepMacs[1]),]
  test2 = dataframe0[which(dataframe0$mac == keepMacs[2]),]
  test3 = dataframe0[which(dataframe0$mac == keepMacs[3]),]
  test4 = dataframe0[which(dataframe0$mac == keepMacs[4]),]
  test5 = dataframe0[which(dataframe0$mac == keepMacs[5]),]
  test6 = dataframe0[which(dataframe0$mac == keepMacs[6]),]
  dataframe = rbind(test1,test2,test3,test4,test5,test6)
  
  
  return(dataframe)
}

Report

Part 2

By subsetting the dataframe and looking at a fixed location and fixed orientation each time, the signal strength over time is approximately normally distributed (left skewed) with a rough average of -55, and the frequencies of signal strenth are dense in the range from -70 to -50. Then, we changed the location and fixed the orientation to see how the signal strength is affected by purely location. We observed that the curve has less skewness and becomes more normally distributed with a rough average at -55.

It can be seen that, at position (0,0), oritation =0, the signal does not decay according to the time, the time series seems stationary around a certain mean value. Other positions and orientations may not agree. The signal strength does fluctuate according to different positions, but there are no gradually varied trend. The histogram shows that the distribution of the signal is not visually symmetric, but it is reasonable to guess there is a trend to approach a normal distribution. More plots are needed. Again, It can be seen that, at position (1,2), oritation =90, the signal does not decay according to the time, the time series seems stationary around a certain mean value. Other positions and orientations may not agree.

Part 3

Following the linear regression model, we can find the k through cross validation. We need to find the signal strength of a certain number of closest neighbor in the training set offline data, and look for the same average signal strength of k closest neighbor in the testing set online data. Then we will take the average of x-coordinates and average of y-coordinates to get the predicted location of (x,y) We use the loss function to check how the prediction is estimated, and try to minimize the error between the truth location and prediction location. Then read online data as what is done above and use the processLine and cleanData functions to modify it, and apply the nearest neighbor method to generate their signal strength to the six access points. ```
